# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nonce-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] In cryptography, **Galois/Counter Mode** (**GCM**) is a mode of operation for symmetric-key cryptographic block ciphers.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The proposal was first published in 2007.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The GCM algorithm belongs to the class of authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) methods.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Given a key K , plaintext P , and associated data $AD$ , GCM encrypts P to produce ciphertext C and an authentication tag T .
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] T is computed from the ciphertext and the unencrypted associated data.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] A recipient who knows K can use the tag to verify that neither the ciphertext nor the associated data had been modified, and then decrypt the ciphertext to recover the plaintext.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM uses a block cipher with a block size of 128 bits, (commonly AES-128) run in counter mode for encryption and uses arithmetic in the Galois field GF(2128) to compute the authentication tag, hence its name.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Different block cipher modes of operation can have significantly different performance with the same block cipher.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] As a counter mode, GCM blocks are independent.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] This allows encryption and decryption to be parallelized, in contrast to modes like cipher block chaining (CBC) where each block relies on the previous one.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM was explicitly designed to be patent-free.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM operates as a counter mode block cipher to produce ciphertext.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] For authentication, the ciphertext blocks are treated as coefficients of a polynomial evaluated at a key-dependent point *H* using finite field arithmetic.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The result is then encrypted, producing an authentication tag that can be used to verify the integrity of the data, so that the encrypted text has the IV, ciphertext, and authentication tag.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM combines the counter mode of encryption with the Galois mode of authentication.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The central feature is the ease of parallel computation of the Galois field multiplication used for authentication.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] This feature has higher throughput than encryption algorithms like CBC that use chaining modes.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The authentication tag is constructed by feeding blocks of data into the GHASH function and encrypting the result.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The second form is an efficient iterative algorithm (each $X_{i}$ depends on $X_{i-1}$ ) produced by applying Horner's method to the first.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Only the final $X_{m+n+1}$ stays an output.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM was designed by John Viega and David A.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] McGrew as a development based on earlier counter-mode authenticated encryption designs, including Carter–Wegman counter mode (CWC mode).
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] In November 2007, NIST announced the release of NIST Special Publication 800-38D *Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation: Galois/Counter Mode (GCM) and GMAC*, making GCM and GMAC official standards.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM mode is used in the IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) Ethernet security, WPA3-Enterprise Wi-Fi security protocol, IEEE 802.11ad (also dubbed WiGig), ANSI (INCITS) Fibre Channel Security Protocols (FC-SP), IEEE P1619.1 tape storage, IETF IPsec standards, SSH, TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] AES-GCM is included in the NSA Suite B Cryptography and its latest replacement in 2018 Commercial National Security Algorithm (CNSA) suite.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM mode is used in the SoftEther VPN server and client, as well as OpenVPN, where AES-GCM ciphers are available via configuration and cipher negotiation since version 2.4.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM requires one block cipher operation and one 128-bit multiplication in the Galois field for each block (128 bits) of encrypted and authenticated data.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The block cipher operations are pipelined or parallelized; the multiplication operations are pipelined and can be parallelized (either by parallelizing the actual operation, by adapting Horner's method per the original NIST submission, or both).
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Intel has added the PCLMULQDQ instruction, which supports carry-less multiplication used in GCM implementations.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] In 2011, SPARC added the XMULX and XMULXHI instructions, which also perform 64 × 64-bit carry-less multiplication.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] In 2015, SPARC added the XMPMUL instruction, which performs XOR multiplication of much larger values, up to 2048 × 2048-bit input values, producing a 4096-bit result.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] These instructions enable fast multiplication over GF(2*n*) and can be used with any field representation.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Performance results are published for GCM on a number of platforms.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Käsper and Schwabe described a "Faster and Timing-Attack Resistant AES-GCM" that achieves 10.68 cycles per byte of AES-GCM authenticated encryption on 64-bit Intel processors.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Dai et al. report 3.5 cycles per byte for the same algorithm when using Intel's AES-NI and PCLMULQDQ instructions.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Shay Gueron and Vlad Krasnov achieved 2.47 cycles per byte on the third-generation Intel processors.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Appropriate patches were prepared for the OpenSSL and NSS libraries.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] When both authentication and encryption need to be performed on a message, interleaving those operations using instruction-level parallelism can increase performance.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] This process is called function stitching, and while in principle it can be applied to any combination of cryptographic algorithms, GCM supports parallel computation which can simplify optimization on some processors.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Manley and Gregg show the ease of optimizing when using function stitching with GCM.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] They present a program generator that takes an annotated C version of a cryptographic algorithm and generates code that runs well on the target processor.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM has been criticized in the embedded world (for example, by Silicon Labs) because the parallel processing is not suited for performant use of cryptographic hardware engines.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] As a result, GCM reduces the performance of encryption for some of the most performance-sensitive devices.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Specialized hardware accelerators for ChaCha20-Poly1305 are less complex compared to AES accelerators.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] GCM is proven to be secure in the concrete security model.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] It is secure when it is used with a block cipher that is indistinguishable from a random permutation; however, security depends on choosing a unique initialization vector for every encryption performed with the same key (*see* stream cipher attack).
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] For any given key and initialization vector value, GCM is limited to encrypting 239−256 bits of plain text (64 GiB).
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] NIST Special Publication 800-38D includes guidelines for initialization vector choice and limits the number of possible initialization vector values for a single key.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] As the security assurance of GCM degrades with more data being processed using the same key, the total number of blocks of plaintext and AD protected during the lifetime of a single key should be limited by 264.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The authentication strength depends on the length of the authentication tag, like with all symmetric message authentication codes.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Using shorter authentication tags with GCM is discouraged.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] The bit-length of the tag, denoted *t*, is a security parameter.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] In general, *t* may be any one of the following five values: 128, 120, 112, 104, or 96.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] For certain applications, *t* may be 64 or 32, but the use of these two tag lengths constrains the length of the input data and the lifetime of the key.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Like with any message authentication code, if the adversary chooses a *t*-bit tag at random, it is expected to be correct for given data with probability measure 2−*t*.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] With GCM, however, an adversary can increase their likelihood of success by choosing tags with *n* words—the total length of the ciphertext plus any added authenticated data (AAD)—with probability measure 2−*t* by a factor of *n*.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] However, these best tags are still dominated by the algorithm's survival measure 1 − *n*⋅2−*t* for arbitrarily large *t*.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Moreover, GCM is not well-suited for use with short tag-lengths or long messages.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Ferguson and Saarinen independently described how an attacker can perform best attacks against GCM authentication, which meets the lower bound on its security.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Ferguson showed that, if *n* denotes the total number of blocks in the encoding (the input to the GHASH function), then there is a method of constructing a targeted ciphertext forgery that is expected to succeed with a probability of approximately *n*⋅2−*t*.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] If the tag length *t* is shorter than 128, then each successful forgery in this attack increases the probability that subsequent targeted forgeries will succeed, and leaks information about the hash subkey *H*.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Eventually, *H* may be compromised entirely, at which point the authentication assurance is completely lost.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Independent of this attack, an adversary may try to systematically guess many different tags for a given input to authenticated decryption and thereby increase the probability that one (or more) of them, eventually, will be considered valid.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] For this reason, the system or protocol that implements GCM should watch and, if necessary, limit the number of unsuccessful verification attempts for each key.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Saarinen described GCM as having weak keys, offering some added analysis into how polynomial hash-based authentication works.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] More precisely, this work describes a particular way of forging a GCM message, given a valid GCM message, that works with probability of about *n*⋅2−128 for messages that are *n* × 128 bits long.
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] However, this work does not show a more effective attack than was previously known; the success probability in observation 1 of this paper matches that of lemma 2 from the INDOCRYPT 2004 analysis (setting *w* = 128 and *l* = *n* × 128).
[src:nonce-management/counter-mode] Saarinen also described a GCM variant Sophie Germain Counter Mode (SGCM) based on Sophie Germain primes.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] In cryptography, a **nonce** is an arbitrary number that can be used just once in a cryptographic communication.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] It is often a random or pseudo-random number issued in an authentication protocol to ensure that each communication session is unique, and therefore that old communications cannot be reused in replay attacks.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Nonces can also be useful as initialization vectors and in cryptographic hash functions.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] A nonce is an arbitrary number used only once in a cryptographic communication, in the spirit of a nonce word.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] They are often random or pseudo-random numbers.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Many nonces also include a timestamp to ensure exact timeliness, though this requires clock synchronisation between organisations.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] The addition of a client nonce ("**cnonce**") helps to improve the security in some ways as implemented in digest access authentication.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] To ensure that a nonce is used only once, it should be time-variant (including a suitably fine-grained timestamp in its value), or generated with enough random bits to ensure an insignificantly low chance of repeating a previously generated value.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Some authors define pseudo-randomness (or unpredictability) as a requirement for a nonce.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Nonce is a word dating back to Middle English for something only used once or temporarily (often with the construction "for the nonce").
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] It descends from the construction "then anes" ("the one [purpose]").
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] A false etymology claiming it to stand for "number used once" or similar is incorrect.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Authentication protocols may use nonces to ensure that old communications cannot be reused in replay attacks.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] For instance, nonces are used in HTTP digest access authentication to calculate an MD5 digest of the password.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] The nonces are different each time the 401 authentication challenge response code is presented, thus making replay attacks virtually impossible.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] The scenario of ordering products over the Internet can provide an example of the usefulness of nonces in replay attacks.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] An attacker could take the encrypted information and—without needing to decrypt—could continue to send a particular order to the supplier, thereby ordering products over and over again under the same name and purchase information.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] The nonce is used to give 'originality' to a given message so that if the company receives any other orders from the same person with the same nonce, it will discard those as invalid orders.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] A nonce may be used to ensure security for a stream cipher.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Where the same key is used for more than one message and then a different nonce is used to ensure that the keystream is different for different messages encrypted with that key; often the message number is used.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Secret nonce values are used by the Lamport signature scheme as a signer-side secret which can be selectively revealed for comparison to public hashes for signature creation and verification.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Nonces are used in proof-of-work systems to vary the input to a cryptographic hash function so as to obtain a hash for a certain input that fulfils certain arbitrary conditions.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] In doing so, it becomes far more difficult to create a "desirable" hash than to verify it, shifting the burden of work onto one side of a transaction or system.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] Similarly, the Bitcoin blockchain hashing algorithm can be tuned to an arbitrary difficulty by changing the required minimum/maximum value of the hash so that the number of bitcoins awarded for new blocks does not increase linearly with increased network computation power as new users join.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] This is likewise achieved by forcing Bitcoin miners to add nonce values to the value being hashed to change the hash algorithm output.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-nonce] As cryptographic hash algorithms cannot easily be predicted based on their inputs, this makes the act of blockchain hashing and the possibility of being awarded bitcoins something of a lottery, where the first "miner" to find a nonce that delivers a desirable hash is awarded bitcoins.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This article provides a simple model to follow when implementing solutions to protect data at rest.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should not be stored using reversible encryption - secure password hashing algorithms should be used instead.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Password Storage Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on storing passwords.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first step in designing any application is to consider the overall architecture of the system, as this will have a huge impact on the technical implementation.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This process should begin with considering the threat model of the application (i.e, who you are trying to protect that data against).
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that many cloud environments provide these services, so these should be taken advantage of where possible.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on this topic.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Which layer(s) are most appropriate will depend on the threat model.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, hardware level encryption is effective at protecting against the physical theft of the server, but will provide no protection if an attacker is able to compromise the server remotely.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The best way to protect sensitive information is to not store it in the first place.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although this applies to all kinds of information, it is most often applicable to credit card details, as they are highly desirable for attackers, and PCI DSS has such stringent requirements for how they must be stored.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, the storage of sensitive information should be avoided.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For symmetric encryption **AES** with a key that's at least **128 bits** (ideally **256 bits**) and a secure mode should be used as the preferred algorithm.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For asymmetric encryption, use elliptical curve cryptography (ECC) with a secure curve such as **Curve25519** as a preferred algorithm.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If ECC is not available and **RSA** must be used, then ensure that the key is at least **2048 bits**.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Many other symmetric and asymmetric algorithms are available which have their own pros and cons, and they may be better or worse than AES or Curve25519 in specific use cases.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases there may be regulatory requirements that limit the algorithms that can be used, such as FIPS 140-2 or PCI DSS.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are various modes that can be used to allow block ciphers (such as AES) to encrypt arbitrary amounts of data, in the same way that a stream cipher would.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These modes have different security and performance characteristics, and a full discussion of them is outside the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Some of the modes have requirements to generate secure initialisation vectors (IVs) and other attributes, but these should be handled automatically by the library.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, authenticated modes should always be used.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] These provide guarantees of the integrity and authenticity of the data, as well as confidentiality.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The most commonly used authenticated modes are **GCM** and **CCM**, which should be used as a first preference.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] If GCM or CCM are not available, then CTR mode or CBC mode should be used.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As these do not provide any guarantees about the authenticity of the data, separate authentication should be implemented, such as using the Encrypt-then-MAC technique.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] ECB should not be used outside of very specific circumstances.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For RSA, it is essential to enable Random Padding.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random Padding is also known as OAEP or Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This class of defense protects against Known Plain Text Attacks by adding randomness at the beginning of the payload.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Padding Schema of PKCS#1 is typically used in this case.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Random numbers (or strings) are needed for various security critical functionality, such as generating encryption keys, IVs, session IDs, CSRF tokens or password reset tokens.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, it is important that these are generated securely, and that it is not possible for an attacker to guess and predict them.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is generally not possible for computers to generate truly random numbers (without special hardware), so most systems and languages provide two different types of randomness.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Pseudo-Random Number Generators (PRNG) provide low-quality randomness that are much faster, and can be used for non-security related functionality (such as ordering results on a page, or randomising UI elements).
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they **must not** be used for anything security critical, as it is often possible for attackers to guess or predict the output.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Cryptographically Secure Pseudo-Random Number Generators (CSPRNG) are designed to produce a much higher quality of randomness (more strictly, a greater amount of entropy), making them safe to use for security-sensitive functionality.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, they are slower and more CPU intensive, can end up blocking in some circumstances when large amounts of random data are requested.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] As such, if large amounts of non-security related randomness are needed, they may not be appropriate.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The table below shows the recommended algorithms for each language, as well as insecure functions that should not be used.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Universally unique identifiers (UUIDs or GUIDs) are sometimes used as a quick way to generate random strings.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Although they can provide a reasonable source of randomness, this will depend on the type or version of the UUID that is created.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Specifically, version 1 UUIDs are comprised of a high precision timestamp and the MAC address of the system that generated them, so are **not random** (although they may be hard to guess, given the timestamp is to the nearest 100ns).
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Type 4 UUIDs are randomly generated, although whether this is done using a CSPRNG will depend on the implementation.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Unless this is known to be secure in the specific language or framework, the randomness of UUIDs should not be relied upon.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Applications should be designed to still be secure even if cryptographic controls fail.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Any information that is stored in an encrypted form should also be protected by additional layers of security.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Application should also not rely on the security of encrypted URL parameters, and should enforce strong access control to prevent unauthorised access to information.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys should be randomly generated using a cryptographically secure function, such as those discussed in the Secure Random Number Generation section.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Keys **should not** be based on common words or phrases, or on "random" characters generated by mashing the keyboard.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where multiple keys are used (such as data separate data-encrypting and key-encrypting keys), they should be fully independent from each other.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Once one of these criteria have been met, a new key should be generated and used for encrypting any new data.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Marking each item with the ID of the key that was used to encrypt it, and storing multiple keys to allow the old data to be decrypted.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The first option should generally be preferred, as it greatly simplifies both the application code and key management processes; however, it may not always be feasible.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Note that old keys should generally be stored for a certain period after they have been retired, in case old backups of copies of the data need to be decrypted.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] It is important that the code and processes required to rotate a key are in place **before** they are required, so that keys can be quickly rotated in the event of a compromise.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Additionally, processes should also be implemented to allow the encryption algorithm or library to be changed, in case a new vulnerability is found in the algorithm or implementation.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Securely storing cryptographic keys is one of the hardest problems to solve, as the application always needs to have some level of access to the keys in order to decrypt the data.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] While it may not be possible to fully protect the keys from an attacker who has fully compromised the application, a number of steps can be taken to make it harder for them to obtain the keys.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, the secure storage mechanisms provided by the operating system, framework or cloud service provider should be used.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] There are many advantages to using these types of secure storage over simply putting keys in configuration files.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In some cases none of these will be available, such as in a shared hosting environment, meaning that it is not possible to obtain a high degree of protection for any encryption keys.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The Secrets Management Cheat Sheet provides more details on securely storing secrets.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should be stored in a separate location from encrypted data.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the data is stored in a database, the keys should be stored in the filesystem.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that if an attacker only has access to one of these (for example through directory traversal or SQL injection), they cannot access both the keys and the data.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the architecture of the environment, it may be possible to store the keys and data on separate systems, which would provide a greater degree of isolation.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] Where possible, encryption keys should themselves be stored in an encrypted form.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] For this to be effective, the KEK must be stored separately from the DEK.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The encrypted DEK can be stored with the data, but will only be usable if an attacker is able to also obtain the KEK, which is stored on another system.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The KEK should also be at least as strong as the DEK.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] The envelope encryption guidance from Google contains further details on how to manage DEKs and KEKs.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] In simpler application architectures (such as shared hosting environments) where the KEK and DEK cannot be stored separately, there is limited value to this approach, as an attacker is likely to be able to obtain both of the keys at the same time.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] However, it can provide an additional barrier to unskilled attackers.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] A key derivation function (KDF) could be used to generate a KEK from user-supplied input (such a passphrase), which would then be used to encrypt a randomly generated DEK.
[src:nonce-management/cryptographic-storage-cheat-sheet] This allows the KEK to be easily changed (when the user changes their passphrase), without needing to re-encrypt the data (as the DEK remains the same).
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In cryptography, an **initialization vector** (**IV**) or **starting variable** is an input to a cryptographic primitive being used to provide the initial state.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The IV is typically required to be random or pseudorandom, but sometimes an IV only needs to be unpredictable or unique.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Randomization is crucial for some encryption schemes to achieve semantic security, a property whereby repeated usage of the scheme under the same key does not allow an attacker to infer relationships between (potentially similar) segments of the encrypted message.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] For block ciphers, the use of an IV is described by the modes of operation.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Some cryptographic primitives require the IV only to be non-repeating, and the required randomness is derived internally.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In this case, the IV is commonly called a nonce (a number used only once), and the primitives (e.g.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] CBC) are considered *stateful* rather than *randomized*.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This is because an IV need not be explicitly forwarded to a recipient but may be derived from a common state updated at both sender and receiver side.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] (In practice, a short nonce is still transmitted along with the message to consider message loss.) An example of stateful encryption schemes is the counter mode of operation, which has a sequence number for a nonce.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The IV size depends on the cryptographic primitive used; for block ciphers it is generally the cipher's block-size.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In encryption schemes, the unpredictable part of the IV has at best the same size as the key to compensate for time/memory/data tradeoff attacks.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] When the IV is chosen at random, the probability of collisions due to the birthday problem must be taken into account.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Traditional stream ciphers such as RC4 do not support an explicit IV as input, and a custom solution for incorporating an IV into the cipher's key or internal state is needed.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Some designs realized in practice are known to be insecure; the WEP protocol is a notable example, and is prone to related-IV attacks.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] A block cipher is one of the most basic primitives in cryptography, and frequently used for data encryption.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] However, by itself, it can only be used to encode a data block of a predefined size, called the block size.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] For example, a single invocation of the AES algorithm transforms a 128-bit plaintext block into a ciphertext block of 128 bits in size.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The key, which is given as one input to the cipher, defines the mapping between plaintext and ciphertext.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] If data of arbitrary length is to be encrypted, a simple strategy is to split the data into blocks each matching the cipher's block size, and encrypt each block separately using the same key.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This method is not secure as equal plaintext blocks get transformed into equal ciphertexts, and a third party observing the encrypted data may easily determine its content even when not knowing the encryption key.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] To hide patterns in encrypted data while avoiding the re-issuing of a new key after each block cipher invocation, a method is needed to randomize the input data.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In 1980, the NIST published a national standard document designated Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) PUB 81, which specified four so-called block cipher modes of operation, each describing a different solution for encrypting a set of input blocks.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The first mode implements the simple strategy described above, and was specified as the electronic codebook (ECB) mode.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In contrast, each of the other modes describe a process where ciphertext from one block encryption step gets intermixed with the data from the next encryption step.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] To initiate this process, an additional input value is required to be mixed with the first block, and which is referred to as an *initialization vector*.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] For example, the cipher-block chaining (CBC) mode requires an unpredictable value, of size equal to the cipher's block size, as additional input.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This unpredictable value is added to the first plaintext block before subsequent encryption.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In turn, the ciphertext produced in the first encryption step is added to the second plaintext block, and so on.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The ultimate goal for encryption schemes is to provide semantic security: by this property, it is practically impossible for an attacker to draw any knowledge from observed ciphertext.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] It can be shown that each of the three additional modes specified by the NIST are semantically secure under so-called chosen-plaintext attacks.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Properties of an IV depend on the cryptographic scheme used.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] A basic requirement is *uniqueness*, which means that no IV may be reused under the same key.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] For block ciphers, repeated IV values devolve the encryption scheme into electronic codebook mode: equal IV and equal plaintext result in equal ciphertext.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In stream cipher encryption uniqueness is crucially important as plaintext may be trivially recovered otherwise.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] both encrypted with the same key and IV.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Many schemes require the IV to be *unpredictable* by an adversary.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This is effected by selecting the IV at random or pseudo-randomly.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In such schemes, the chance of a duplicate IV is negligible, but the effect of the birthday problem must be considered.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] As for the uniqueness requirement, a predictable IV may allow recovery of (partial) plaintext.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Consider a scenario where a legitimate party called Alice encrypts messages using the cipher-block chaining mode.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] be Eve's guess for the first plaintext block.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Depending on whether the IV for a cryptographic scheme must be random or only unique the scheme is either called *randomized* or *stateful*.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] While randomized schemes always require the IV chosen by a sender to be forwarded to receivers, stateful schemes allow sender and receiver to share a common IV state, which is updated in a predefined way at both sides.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Block cipher processing of data is usually described as a mode of operation.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Modes are primarily defined for encryption as well as authentication, though newer designs exist that combine both security solutions in so-called authenticated encryption modes.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] While encryption and authenticated encryption modes usually take an IV matching the cipher's block size, authentication modes are commonly realized as deterministic algorithms, and the IV is set to zero or some other fixed value.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In stream ciphers, IVs are loaded into the keyed internal secret state of the cipher, after which a number of cipher rounds are executed prior to releasing the first bit of output.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] The 802.11 encryption algorithm called WEP (short for Wired Equivalent Privacy) used a short, 24-bit IV, leading to reused IVs with the same key, which led to it being easily cracked.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Packet injection allowed for WEP to be cracked in times as short as several seconds.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This ultimately led to the deprecation of WEP.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In cipher-block chaining mode (CBC mode), the IV need not be secret, but must be unpredictable (In particular, for any given plaintext, it must not be possible to predict the IV that will be associated to the plaintext in advance of the generation of the IV.) at encryption time.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] Additionally for the output feedback mode (OFB mode), the IV must be unique.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] In particular, the (previously) common practice of re-using the last ciphertext block of a message as the IV for the next message is insecure (for example, this method was used by SSL 2.0).
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] If an attacker knows the IV (or the previous block of ciphertext) before he specifies the next plaintext, he can check his guess about plaintext of some block that was encrypted with the same key before.
[src:nonce-management/initialization-vector] This is known as the TLS CBC IV attack, also called the BEAST attack.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Both ciphers are built on a pseudorandom function based on add–rotate–XOR (ARX) operations — 32-bit addition, bitwise addition (XOR) and rotation operations.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The core function maps a 256-bit key, a 64-bit nonce, and a 64-bit counter to a 512-bit block of the key stream (a Salsa version with a 128-bit key also exists).
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] This gives Salsa20 and ChaCha the unusual advantage that the user can efficiently seek to any position in the key stream in constant time.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Salsa20 offers speeds of around 4–14 cycles per byte in software on modern x86 processors, and reasonable hardware performance.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] It is not patented, and Bernstein has written several public domain implementations optimized for common architectures.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Internally, the cipher uses bitwise addition ⊕ (exclusive OR), 32-bit addition mod 232 ⊞, and constant-distance rotation operations <<< on an internal state of sixteen 32-bit words.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Using only add-rotate-xor operations avoids the possibility of timing attacks in software implementations.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The internal state is made of sixteen 32-bit words arranged as a 4×4 matrix.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The constant words spell "expand 32-byte k" in ASCII (i.e. the 4 words are "expa", "nd 3", "2-by", and "te k") as a nothing-up-my-sleeve number.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Odd-numbered rounds apply `QR(a, b, c, d)` to each of the four columns in the 4×4 matrix, and even-numbered rounds apply it to each of the four rows.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] An implementation in C/C++ appears below.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In the last line, the mixed array is added, word by word, to the original array to obtain its 64-byte key stream block.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] This is important because the mixing rounds on their own are *invertible*.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In other words, applying the reverse operations would produce the original 4×4 matrix, including the key.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Adding the mixed array to the original makes it impossible to recover the input.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Salsa20 performs 20 rounds of mixing on its input.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] However, reduced-round variants Salsa20/8 and Salsa20/12 using 8 and 12 rounds respectively have also been introduced.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] These variants were introduced to complement the original Salsa20, not to replace it, and perform better in the eSTREAM benchmarks than Salsa20, though with a correspondingly lower security margin.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2008, Bernstein proposed a variant of Salsa20 with 192-bit nonces called XSalsa20.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] XSalsa20 is provably secure if Salsa20 is secure, but is more suitable for applications where longer nonces are desired.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Specifically, the 256 bits of output used are those corresponding to the non-secret portions of the input: indexes 0, 5, 10, 15, 6, 7, 8 and 9.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Salsa20/12 has been selected as a Phase 3 design for Profile 1 (software) by the eSTREAM project, receiving the highest weighted voting score of any Profile 1 algorithm at the end of Phase 2.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] As of 2015, there are no published attacks on Salsa20/12 or the full Salsa20/20; the best attack known breaks 8 of the 12 or 20 rounds.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2005, Paul Crowley reported an attack on Salsa20/5 with an estimated time complexity of 2165 and won Bernstein's US$1000 prize for "most interesting Salsa20 cryptanalysis".
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] This attack and all subsequent attacks are based on truncated differential cryptanalysis.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2006, Fischer, Meier, Berbain, Biasse, and Robshaw reported an attack on Salsa20/6 with estimated time complexity of 2177, and a related-key attack on Salsa20/7 with estimated time complexity of 2217.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2007, Tsunoo *et al.* announced a cryptanalysis of Salsa20 which breaks 8 out of 20 rounds to recover the 256-bit secret key in 2255 operations, using 211.37 keystream pairs.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] However, this attack does not seem to be competitive with the brute force attack.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2008, Aumasson, Fischer, Khazaei, Meier, and Rechberger reported a cryptanalytic attack against Salsa20/7 with a time complexity of 2151, and they reported an attack against Salsa20/8 with an estimated time complexity of 2251.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] This attack makes use of the new concept of probabilistic neutral key bits for probabilistic detection of a truncated differential.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The attack can be adapted to break Salsa20/7 with a 128-bit key.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2012, the attack by Aumasson et al. was improved by Shi et al. against Salsa20/7 (128-bit key) to a time complexity of 2109 and Salsa20/8 (256-bit key) to 2250.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2013, Mouha and Preneel published a proof that 15 rounds of Salsa20 was 128-bit secure against differential cryptanalysis.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2025, Dey et al. reported a cryptanalytic attack against Salsa20/8 with a time complexity of 2245.84 and data amounting to 299.47.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In 2008, Bernstein published the closely related **ChaCha** family of ciphers, which aim to increase the diffusion per round while achieving the same or slightly better performance.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The Aumasson et al. paper also attacks ChaCha, achieving one round fewer (for 256-bit ChaCha6 with complexity 2139, ChaCha7 with complexity 2248, and 128-bit ChaCha6 within 2107) but claims that the attack fails to break 128-bit ChaCha7.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Like Salsa20, ChaCha's initial state includes a 128-bit constant, a 256-bit key, a 64-bit counter, and a 64-bit nonce (in the original version; as described later, a version of ChaCha from RFC 7539 is slightly different), arranged as a 4×4 matrix of 32-bit words.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The constant is the same as Salsa20 ("expand 32-byte k").
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Notice that this version updates each word twice, while Salsa20's quarter round updates each word only once.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In addition, the ChaCha quarter-round diffuses changes more quickly.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] On average, after changing 1 input bit the Salsa20 quarter-round will change 8 output bits while ChaCha will change 12.5 output bits.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The ChaCha quarter round has the same number of adds, xors, and bit rotates as the Salsa20 quarter-round, but the fact that two of the rotates are multiples of 8 allows for a small optimization on some architectures including x86.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Additionally, the input formatting has been rearranged to support an efficient SSE implementation optimization discovered for Salsa20.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Rather than alternating rounds down columns and across rows, they are performed down columns and along diagonals.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Like Salsa20, ChaCha arranges the sixteen 32-bit words in a 4×4 matrix.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha20 uses 10 iterations of the double round.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha is the basis of the BLAKE hash function, a finalist in the NIST hash function competition, and its faster successors BLAKE2 and BLAKE3.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] It also defines a variant using sixteen 64-bit words (1024 bits of state), with correspondingly adjusted rotation constants.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Although not announced by Bernstein, the security proof of XSalsa20 extends straightforwardly to an analogous *XChaCha* cipher.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Use the key and the first 128 bits of the nonce (in input words 12 through 15) to form a ChaCha input block, then perform the block operation (omitting the final addition).
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Output words 0–3 and 12–15 (those words corresponding to non-key words of the input) then form the key used for ordinary ChaCha (with the last 64 bits of nonce and 64 bits of block counter).
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Aumasson argues in 2020 that 8 rounds of ChaCha (ChaCha8) probably provides enough resistance to future cryptanalysis for the same security level, yielding a 2.5× speedup.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] A compromise ChaCha12 (based on the eSTREAM recommendation of a 12-round Salsa) also sees some use.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The eSTREAM benchmarking suite includes ChaCha8 and ChaCha12.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Google had selected ChaCha20 along with Bernstein's Poly1305 message authentication code in SPDY, which was intended as a replacement for TLS over TCP.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] In the process, they proposed a new authenticated encryption construction combining both algorithms, which is called ChaCha20-Poly1305.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha20 and Poly1305 are now used in the QUIC protocol, which replaces SPDY and is used by HTTP/3.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Shortly after Google's adoption for TLS, both the ChaCha20 and Poly1305 algorithms were also used for a new `chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com` cipher in OpenSSH.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Subsequently, this made it possible for OpenSSH to avoid any dependency on OpenSSL, via a compile-time option.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha20 is also used for the `arc4random` random number generator in FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and NetBSD operating systems, instead of the broken RC4, and in DragonFly BSD for the CSPRNG subroutine of the kernel.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Starting from version 4.8, the Linux kernel uses the ChaCha20 algorithm to generate data for the nonblocking /dev/urandom device.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha8 is used for the default PRNG in Golang.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha20 usually offers better performance than the more prevalent Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithm on systems where the CPU does not feature AES acceleration (such as the AES instruction set for x86 processors).
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] As a result, ChaCha20 is sometimes preferred over AES in certain use cases involving mobile devices, which mostly use ARM-based CPUs.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Specialized hardware accelerators for ChaCha20 are also less complex compared to AES accelerators.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] ChaCha20-Poly1305 (IETF version; see below) is the exclusive algorithm used by the WireGuard VPN system, as of protocol version 1.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] An implementation reference for ChaCha20 has been published in RFC 7539.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The IETF's implementation modified Bernstein's published algorithm by changing the 64-bit nonce and 64-bit block counter to a 96-bit nonce and 32-bit block counter.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] The name was not changed when the algorithm was modified, as it is cryptographically insignificant (both form what a cryptographer would recognize as a 128-bit nonce), but the interface change could be a source of confusion for developers.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Because of the reduced block counter, the maximum message length that can be safely encrypted by the IETF's variant is 232 blocks of 64 bytes (256 GiB).
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] For applications where this is not enough, such as file or disk encryption, RFC 7539 proposes using the original algorithm with 64-bit nonce.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Use of ChaCha20 in IKE and IPsec has been standardized in RFC 7634.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] Standardization of its use in TLS is published in RFC 7905.
[src:nonce-management/salsa20] RFC 8439 merges in some errata and adds additional security considerations.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Stream ciphers, where plaintext bits are combined with a cipher bit stream by an exclusive-or operation (xor), can be secure if used properly.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Stream ciphers are vulnerable to attack if the same key is used more than once (a depth of two or greater).
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Suppose messages *A* and *B* of the same length are both encrypted using the same key, *K*.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] The stream cipher produces a string of bits *C(K)* of the same length as the messages.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] If one message is longer than the other, the adversary can truncate the longer message to the size of the shorter one, revealing only that portion.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] In other words, if two messages are encrypted with the same key, an attacker can recover *A xor B*, which is a form of running key cipher.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Even if neither message is known, as long as both are in a natural language, such a cipher can often be broken by hand methods.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] During World War II, British cryptanalyst John Tiltman accomplished this with the Lorenz cipher (dubbed "Tunny").
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] With an average personal computer, such ciphers can usually be broken in minutes.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] If one message is known, the solution is trivial.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Another situation where recovery is trivial is when traffic-flow security measures require each station to send a continuous stream of cipher bits, with null characters (e.g.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] *LTRS* in Baudot) transmitted when there is no real traffic.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] This is common in military communications.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] In that case, if the transmission channel is not fully loaded, there is a high likelihood that one of the ciphertext streams will consist only of nulls.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] The NSA has taken extensive measures to prevent keys from being reused.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] In the 1960s, encryption systems often included a punched card reader for loading keys.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] The mechanism would automatically cut the card in half when it was removed, preventing reuse.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] One way to avoid this problem is to use an initialization vector (IV), sent in the clear, that is combined with a secret master key to create a one-time key for the stream cipher.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] This is done in several systems that use the popular stream cipher RC4, including Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP), Wi-Fi Protected Access (WPA), and Ciphersaber.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] One of the problems with WEP was that its IV was too short (24 bits).
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] This meant there was a high likelihood that the same IV would be reused if more than a few thousand packets were sent with the same master key (see birthday attack), subjecting those packets to the key reuse attack.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] This problem was addressed in WPA by changing the "master" key frequently.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Suppose an adversary knows the exact content of all or part of a message.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] As part of a man in the middle attack or replay attack, they can alter the content without knowing the key, *K*.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] For example, if they know a portion of the message contains the ASCII string *"$1000.00"*, they can change it to *"$9500.00"* by XORing that portion of the ciphertext with the string: *"$1000.00" xor "$9500.00"*.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Since a string XORed with itself produces all zeros, and a string of zeros XORed with another string leaves that string unchanged, the result *C(K) xor "$9500.00"* is what the ciphertext would have been if $9500 were the original amount.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Bit-flipping attacks can be prevented by including a message authentication code, which increases the likelihood that tampering will be detected.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Stream ciphers combine a secret key with an agreed initialization vector (IV) to produce a pseudo-random sequence that is periodically re-synchronized.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] A "chosen IV" attack relies on finding particular IVs which, taken together, may reveal information about the secret key.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Typically, multiple pairs of IVs are chosen and differences in the generated key streams are then analyzed statistically for a linear correlation and/or an algebraic Boolean relation (see also Differential cryptanalysis).
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] If choosing particular values of the initialization vector exposes a non-random pattern in the generated sequence, the attack can recover some bits and shorten the effective key length.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] A symptom of such an attack would be frequent re-synchronization.
[src:nonce-management/stream-cipher-attacks] Modern stream ciphers include steps to adequately mix the secret key with the initialization vector, usually by performing many initial rounds.
